<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1872-09-26T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1872-09-26T00:00:00-05:00" n="367" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d367">
                        <head>No. 367.<lb/><hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Hale</persName> to Mr. <persName type="to">Thomas</persName>.</hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department
                                        of State</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1872-09-26"><hi rend="italic">September</hi> 26,
                                    1872</date>.</dateline>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 8.]</seg>
                        </opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: Your dispatch No. 2, under date of July
                            26, relating to recent political disturbances in Peru, has been
                            received.</p>
                        <p>The indignation of the people of Peru at a cruel assassination and an
                            attempted usurpation and overthrow of a representative government
                            commands admiration, and their calm return to order gives promise of a
                            stable condition of public affairs.</p>
                        <p>Your reply to the circular-note of Doctor Caso’s is approved.</p>
                        <p>I am, &amp;c,</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>CHARLES HALE,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Acting
                                Secretary.</hi></signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                </body></text></TEI>